Classroom instructors need ways to quickly determine the experience of their class, and what material to cover each semester. School administrators need to prove program goals are met, and predict future road-maps. We demonstrate a tool and method to automatically combine Individual Concept Maps (ICMs) together into a Collective Concept Map (CCM), for use in a New Model for Educational Program Assessments (NMEPA). Each student creates an ICM at key points throughout a semester, which shows the development of their knowledge. The combination of those ICMs into a CCM summarizes the knowledge of each class as a whole, compared to an ''Expert-CM'' pre-created using domain expertise. Abstraction Filters enable a rapid quantitative analysis of learning effectiveness at both the group and individual level. Through Longitudinal Studies, Administrators use this information to assess a program overall, and to compare the performance of all programs using this NMEPA.